she describes as his "acerbic critique of ideology." She rescues Amichai's poetry from complacent appropriations, showing in the process how his work obliges us to rethink major issues in literary studies, including metaphor, intertextuality, translation, and the politics of poetic form. In spotlighting his deeply egalitarian outlook, this book makes the experimental, iconoclastic Amichai newly compelling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aIsraeli poetryxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aJewish poetryxHistory and criticismx20th centuryxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 4aIntertextuality. 4aIsrael/Palestine. 4aLiminality. 4aLiterary Historiography. 4aMetaphor. 4aModern Hebrew Literature. 4aModernism. 4aPolitical Poetry. 4aTranslation Studies. 4aYehuda Amichai. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804797214zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797214.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles